Preheat your oven to 200°C. Pour a good glug of @oil{} onto a #baking tray{} and pop on the top shelf of your oven. Bring a #large saucepan{} of water to the boil on high heat with 0.5 tsp of @salt{0.5%tsp}.

Peel the @potatoes{700%g}, chop them into 4cm chunks. Add the potatoes to the boiling water and cook for ~{7-8%minutes} or until the edges have softened when you poke them with a knife.

Trim the @carrots{2} and @parsnips{2}, then halve lengthways (no need to peel). Chop into roughly 1cm wide, 5cm long batons. Pick the @rosemary{½ bunch} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks).

Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{}, pop back into the pan then sprinkle on half the @plain flour{1.5%tbsp} and half of the rosemary. Give your pan a shake to fluff up the potato. Take your hot baking tray out of your oven, carefully transfer your potatoes onto it in a single layer, turning in the oil. Season with @salt{}.

Roast the potatoes on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{45-50%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Season the @British beef roasting joint{450%g} with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Transfer to a baking tray.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Roast on the middle shelf of your oven for ~{30-35%minutes} (depending on size) for medium rare. Add an extra ~{5%minutes} if you like your beef more cooked. Rest wrapped loosely in #foil{} for at least ~{10%minutes} before slicing.

> IMPORTANT: The beef is safe to eat when the outside is browned and cooked.

Meanwhile, pop the carrots and parsnips onto a baking tray. Drizzle with @oil{}, @honey{15%ml} and the remaining rosemary. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss and bake on the bottom shelf of the oven, until tender, ~{30-35%minutes}. Turn halfway.

Meanwhile, put a #saucepan{} on medium high heat, add half the @unsalted butter{30%g}. Allow to melt, then stir in the remaining @plain flour{1.5%tbsp} to create a smooth paste. You've made a roux! Cook, stirring until the roux is a medium brown colour, gradually stir in the @water for the gravy{400%ml} and @red wine stock paste{28%g}. Bring to the boil, carefully stirring out any lumps that form. Lower the heat and simmer until the gravy has thickened to your liking, ~{15-20%minutes}. Add a splash of water if necessary.

Quarter the @sweetheart cabbage{1} lengthways. About ~{10%minutes} before the beef comes out of the oven, heat the remaining butter and a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} over medium high heat. Add the cabbage and cook until golden brown, ~{3-4%minutes} each cut side. Once the beef has come out of the oven and is resting, pop the cabbage on the tray it was on and roast until tender, ~{9-10%minutes} (don't wash up the #frying pan{}).

Return the frying pan to medium high heat and add the @British smoked bacon lardons{60%g} and cook, stirring, until golden brown all over, ~{3-4%minutes}. Add the @red wine vinegar{12%ml} and cook until evaporated. Once the cabbage is cooked, pour the bacon mixture over it and set aside.

When everything is ready, reheat the gravy if you need to. Thinly slice the beef and arrange on plates. Serve the veggies and potatoes alongside. Add any beef resting juices or some water to the gravy to loosen it up if necessary, spoon over and enjoy!